  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.1415" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Johns Hopkins University<lb/>Baltimore, Md Sep. 17, 84</dateline>
        <opener>Prof. Hugo Schuchardt,<lb/> My dear Sir,</opener>
        <p>Your kind letter of Aug. 26<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> has just been received on my return from <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5972">
Canada</placeName> where I have spent two months at work on the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.922">Canadian French language</ref>. Accept my best thanks. I am sorry to say that I have no more copies of my little article on the Creole<note
            n="1" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Es liegen bis jetzt keine Informationen über diesen Artikeln vor.</note> which is very imperfect compared with your exhaustive studies, nevertheless if I can find a copy of it I shall be only too glad to send it to you to help complete your collection. I cannot <pb
            facs="#IMG.2"
            n="2"/> thank you too much furthermore for your great kindness in recommending so warmly Prof. <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2427">Pogatscher</persName>
          <note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2427">Alois Pogatscher</persName> (1852-1935) korrespondierte ebenfalls mit Schuchardt [Bei <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.1600">Wolf (1993)</ref>

            </bibl>, Briefe 08889 - 08959].</note> &amp; for sending me his little brochure on Volks Etymologie [sic].<note
            n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>

Pogatscher, Alois. 1884<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">. Zur volksetymologie: nachträge und bemerkungen zu Andresens und Palmers volksetymologischen schriftenur</hi>. Graz: Steierm. Landes-Oberrealschule.
</bibl>
          </note> It is possible the position with reference to which I wrote you nearly three months ago may not be filled for some little time, but when the matter does come up I shall take great pleasure in naming the gentleman whom you so highly recommend and support him with the expression of your very valuable estimation.</p>
        <p>I have just returned from <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5972">
Canada</placeName> where I have col<pb facs="#IMG.3"
            n="3"/>lected an immense mass of material and shall be kept very busy during the winter working it up. As I have extended my observations North and South of the St. Lawrence River, I am prepared to show that the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.3341">
Canadian French</ref> is no Patois as has been supposed but is one of the most interesting phases of language I have ever examined, especially for the preservation of its old forms. I shall take a great pleasure in sending you whatever I may write on this subject. I am extremely sorry to hear that your most valuable services to science have been in any measure lessened by illness for I have long been accustom<pb
            facs="#IMG.4" n="4"/>ed to admire you as the leading spirit of <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.922">Romance Philology</ref> and have regarded your power of work as something wonderful. Hoping that this may find you greatly improved, I am, with renewed thanks, my dear sir,</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours most truly,</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1447">A. M. Elliott</persName>. </signed>
        </closer>
        <postscript>
          <p>Prof. H. Schuchardt.</p>
          <p>Univ. of Graz.</p>
        </postscript>
      </div>
